[1]
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 2004 17:38:28 -0800 (PST)
From: John Herbert <j_a_herbert@yahoo.com>
Source: KOCO Channel 5 Channeloklahoma.com [edited]
<http://www.channeloklahoma.com/news/2940595/detail.html>

Officials Say Bacteria Caused Illnesses Among Visiting Parents, Students
------------------------------------------------------------------------
A bacterium that is connected to Legionnaires' disease has been confirmed
in Oklahoma, and state health officials said Mon, 22 Mar 2004 that a
Oklahoma hotel was the likely source.
Eyewitness News 5 learned that the Comfort Suites at Interstate 44 and
Meridian was the location where people who were in Oklahoma City for a
basketball tournament were staying when they became ill.
The state Health Department and the Oklahoma City-County Health Department
said Mon, 22 Mar 2004, that the bacterium (_Legionella pneumophila_) caused
several upper respiratory illnesses among people who stayed in the hotel.
Officials told Eyewitness News 5's Kevin Peters that 66 people from Texas
tested positive for the bacterium. 13 people from Houston developed upper
respiratory illnesses, officials said.
The bacterium can lead to Legionnaires' disease -- a severe infection that
includes pneumonia. It can also cause a milder illness called Pontiac
fever. Officials said 2 Houston residents were in the hospital with
Pontiac fever Mon evening, 22 Mar 2004.
