[2]
Date: Mon, 22 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail promed@promedmail.org
Source: Houston Chronicle [edited]
<http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/ssistory.mpl/metropolitan/2462482>

50-plus tested for cause of Legionnaires'
-----------------------------------------
More than 50 home-schooled students and others from Montgomery County
(Texas) have been tested for the bacterium that causes Legionnaires'
disease after returning from an Oklahoma basketball tournament with
symptoms of the illness. The source of the illness apparently was an
Oklahoma City hotel where about 70 players, parents, and others stayed last
week during the National Christian Homeschool Basketball Championship &
Family Conference, health officials there said.
Although an Oklahoma state Health Department spokeswoman said 13 people
from The Woodlands and nearby areas had tested positive for _Legionella
pneumophilia_ bacteria, health officials in Montgomery County confirmed
only 1 case and Texas health officials said 2 had been confirmed thus
far. However, the test results in most cases had not been completed, and
more confirmations are likely, said Dr. Herbert DuPont, chief of internal
medicine at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital in Houston.
The conflicting numbers could not immediately be resolved. However, DuPont
said the symptoms reported by most patients at the St. Luke's facility in
The Woodlands appeared to fit those of Pontiac fever -- a relatively mild,
flulike illness of short duration caused by the same bacteria that cause
Legionnaires' disease. Both illnesses are treatable with antibiotics and
neither is contagious, DuPont said. While the symptoms persist, those who
were exposed should see their doctors, but children may go to school and
adults to work if they feel able, he said.
Pontiac fever, named for an outbreak in Pontiac, Mich., usually passes
after a few days and does not involve pneumonia, DuPont said. By contrast,
he said, patients with Legionnaires' disease do get pneumonia and have
symptoms much more extreme than those of flu. Legionnaires' disease, named
for a 1976 outbreak at an American Legion convention at the Bellevue
Stratford Hotel in Philadelphia, is deadly for about 1 in 10 who contract
it. But most who succumb have other weakening conditions such as cancer,
heart or lung illness, or extreme diabetes, DuPont said. The bacteria are
spread through such means as heated water and moisture in air conditioning
ducts, he said.
About 70 players and others who stayed at the Comfort Suites on Interstate
40 in Oklahoma City were exposed, and the city-county health department
shut down the pool and spa where the outbreak is thought to have started,
said department spokesman H.R. Holman. The department is trying to reach
everyone who stayed in the hotel recently, Holman said. A desk clerk
declined to comment, except to say the hotel remains open.
Leslea Bennett Webb, spokeswoman for the Oklahoma Department of Health,
said the patients' symptoms included fever of 102 to 104 degrees F,
headache, and muscle aches. Most of the cases were reported Sat, 20 Mar
2004, she said, but the patients, ranging in age from 4 to 44, said they
had felt ill since Thu, 18 Mar 2004. Doug McBride, spokesman for the Texas
Department of Health, said 2 Texas patients, both from the Houston area,
are reported to have tested positive for the bacteria. He would not
identify them or the hospital where they were tested. Neither McBride nor
Webb could explain the difference between the Texas and Oklahoma numbers.
Jennifer Reynolds-Sanchez of the University of Texas Medical Branch in
Galveston, which provides public health services for Montgomery County
under contract, gave figures different from either. At Memorial Hermann The
Woodlands Hospital, 31 people were tested, but the results were not
available Monday, Reynolds-Sanchez said. 2 of those complaining of symptoms
were admitted, said Memorial Hermann spokeswoman Jamie O'Roark. At St.
Luke's Community Hospital-The Woodlands, 20 were tested, one was confirmed
to have the bacteria, and results were still pending for the others,
Reynolds-Sanchez said.
[Byline: Rad Sallee]
